ce:section.ce:para:
The parameters listed in Table 4
                         include molar mass (M), density (ρ), molar volume (Vm), oxygen packing density (OPD), ionic concentration (N), and interionic spacing (Ri). Density decreases when Nb2O5 replaces Bi2O3 in the studied glass series (0.25-x) Bi2O3 - x Nb2O5- 0.75V2O5 (Fig. 3
                        ). It decreases from 4.6 to 3.6 g/cm3. This decrease can be justified if we consider the molar masses of the oxides. Bi2O3 has a much higher molar mass than Nb2O5 (M (Bi2O3) = 465.96 g/mol ≫ M (Nb2O5) = 265.81 g/mol). The fact that the lower density of niobium (8.57 g/cm3) substitutes the high density of bismuth (9.78 g/cm3) further supports this conclusion. The observed rise in molar volume suggests that Nb2O5 promotes a greater dispersion within the glass network.
